7. Follow Up With Purpose, Not Pressure
Most conversions happen in follow-ups, not the first email. BDR teams that implement structured, value-driven follow-ups see significantly higher reply rates.

Effective follow-ups should:

Add a new insight or resource

Restate the value proposition concisely

Reference previous outreach without guilt-tripping

Offer alternative CTAs such as a resource, case study, or question

Example:

“Circling back in case this slipped through. Many IT leaders we support are prioritizing automation this quarter. Would it help if I sent a quick case study showing how teams are accelerating pipeline using targeted content syndication?”

This follow-up is respectful, helpful, and relevant.

Bonus: Questions BDRs Should Ask Before Sending Any Email
To ensure your outreach is strong, ask yourself:

Does the email demonstrate genuine relevance to the recipient’s role and priorities?

Is the message concise and easy to skim?

Am I offering value or just asking for time?

Does the CTA lower resistance?

Would I respond if I were the recipient?

If you answer yes to all five, your email is likely ready to send.

